IRS990.ActivityOrMissionDesc: KETCH Housing is a housing project for low income, elderly and/or developmentally disabled. It is not organized for profit. Instead, it is organized exclusively for charitable, educational and scientific purposes.
IRS990.MissionDesc: To provide elderly and/or handicapped persons with housing facilities and services specifically designed to meet their physical, social and psychological needs and to promote their health, security, happiness and usefulness in longer living, charges for such facilities and services to be predicated upon the provisions, maintenance and operation thereof on the nonprofit basis; and to engage in such lawful activities and acts as the laws of the State of Kansas may allow in furtherance of the aforementioned purposes.
IRS990.Desc: Almond Tree Project is a housing project for low income, elderly and developmentally disabled pursuant to Section 202 of the National Housing Act. The Project is regulated by the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development (HUD) with respect to rental charges and operating methods. The Project has a twenty-year housing assistance contract with HUD and rental operations began in February 1988. The Project contains fifty units located in Wichita, Kansas, one of which is non-income producing for the house manager. The Project is Section 8 rent assistance and Section 202 direct loan program.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Section A, Line 3
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: The Project contracts with Weigand-Omega Management, Inc (WOM) for maintenance services. The Project reimburses WOM for all payroll, payroll taxes, and fringe benefits costs related to those services and the on-site building manager.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, Line 11b
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: A copy of Form 990 is presented to all members of the board for review.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, Line 12c
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: Per KETCH policy (14.1), no agreement, contract or otherwise binding exchange, either verbal or written, shall take place between a Board member(s) of KETCH that shall result in the unfair personal gain or reward to either party. Examples of such conflicts include but not limited to the following: Unfair awarding of construction contracts, discriminatory vendor selection, breaching of EEO/AAP recruitment practices, etc. KETCH bylaws provide conflict of interest rules for board members. Board members must sign a conflict of interest statement of understanding.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Section B, Line 15
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: All compensation decisions for the President/CEO are made by the KETCH Board of Directors, all of whom are required to be independent for the organization and its employees. Compensation decisions upon initial hire are documented in the employment contract between the KETCH Board of Directors and the President/CEO. When the position is vacant, the Vice President of Human Resources assists the selection committee of the KETCH Board of Directors in determining desired range of base pay and benefits by providing them with market comparison data from similar organizations within the geographic area.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: Form 990, Part VI, Section C, Line 19
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: The governing documents, conflict of interest policy and financial statements are available to the public upon request at 1006 E Waterman Wichita KS 67211 or www.KETCH.org. Additionally, the following information is available online at www.KETCH.org: Notice of Privacy Practices, Accreditation information and the KETCH Annual report.
